 {challenges.map(c => (
 <div class="card-light p-5">
 <div class="font-semibold text-body-text mb-1">{c.title}</div>
 <p class="text-sm text-muted-text leading-relaxed">{c.desc}</p>
 </div>
 ))}
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Love and relationships -->
 <section class="py-16 px-4">
 <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2">
 Life path 6 in love &amp; relationships
 </h2>
 <div class="space-y-4 text-muted-text leading-relaxed">
 <p>
 LP6 is arguably the most devoted partner in numerology. When they commit, they commit fully. They mean every bit of it. Being loved by an LP6 means being seen, consistently shown up for, and, if the relationship is working, cared for in ways that most people don't even realize they needed until they experience it.
 </p>
 <p>
 The complexity in LP6 relationships comes in two related forms. First, the giving imbalance: LP6 often gives more than they receive, and over time that creates an internal ledger of unacknowledged sacrifices that eventually becomes resentment. The 6 who learns to name their needs clearly, rather than expecting partners to intuit them, has dramatically better relationships.
 </p>
 <p>
 Second, the improvement impulse: LP6's care can express itself as a running commentary on how the partner could be better, healthier, more organized, more present. This is love in LP6's language. It doesn't always land that way. Partners who need to feel accepted as they are rather than continuously nudged toward a better version of themselves can find this pattern hard to live with.
 </p>
 <p>
 The natural matches for LP6 are LP2 (mutual warmth, shared values, real emotional fluency), LP4 (stable home, matching commitment to the long term), and LP9 (shared orientation toward care and something larger than themselves). The more effortful pairings are LP5 (freedom versus commitment) and LP1 (independence versus connection).
 </p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Compatibility table -->
 <section id="compatibility" style="padding:3rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-card-bg);">
 <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2" style="text-align:center;">
 Life path 6 compatibility
 </h2>
 <p class="text-center text-muted-text mb-10 max-w-xl mx-auto">
 How life path 6 pairs with each of the other life path numbers - based on shared values, complementary traits, and where the tension tends to surface.
 </p>
 <div class="overflow-x-auto">
 <table style="width:100%;font-size:0.875rem;border-collapse:collapse;border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:8px;overflow:hidden;box-shadow:0 2px 12px rgba(26,21,40,0.07);">
 <thead>
 <tr>
 <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider">Life Path</th>
 <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider">Archetype</th>
 <th class="text-center px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider">Match</th>
 <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider hidden md:table-cell">Notes</th>
 </tr>
 </thead>
 <tbody>
 {compatibility.map(row => (
 <tr>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-violet text-base">{row.lp}</td>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 text-body-text font-medium whitespace-nowrap">{row.label}</td>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center whitespace-nowrap">
 {Array.from({length: 5}).map((_, i) => (
 <span class={i < row.score ? "text-gold" : "text-border/40"}>★</span>
 ))}
 </td>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 text-muted-text hidden md:table-cell">{row.verdict}</td>
 </tr>
 ))}
 </tbody>
 </table>
 </div>
 <p class="text-xs text-muted-text mt-4 text-center">
 Compatibility ratings reflect general patterns across life path numbers. Individual charts always add nuance.
 </p>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Career -->
 <section class="py-16 px-4">
 <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2">
 Career paths for life path 6
 </h2>
 <div class="space-y-4 text-muted-text leading-relaxed">
 <p>
 LP6 thrives in work with a direct human dimension. Their care and attentiveness become genuine professional assets. Healthcare, counseling, therapy, teaching, social work, and community development all draw naturally on what LP6 already does. So does anything involving aesthetics and harmony: interior design, landscape architecture, the hospitality industry, wedding planning, and the arts.
 </p>
 <p>
 LP6 is often exceptional in roles where the job is to hold a complex emotional environment together. The manager who keeps the team from fragmenting during a difficult period. The nurse everyone on the floor trusts. The therapist whose clients make real progress. The caring presence isn't just a personal quality. In the right context it's a high-value professional skill.
 </p>
 <p>
 The career risk for LP6 is taking on too much for too long. LP6 tends to absorb other people's stress, take on extra responsibility out of a sense of duty, and not ask for support until they're already depleted. Building boundaries into their professional life, deciding in advance what they will and won't absorb, is practical self-preservation, not selfishness.
 </p>
 <p>
 What LP6 needs from a career: the sense that what they do helps someone, a collaborative environment with real relationships, and some degree of beauty or craft in the work itself. The purely transactional, high-stress, take-no-prisoners kind of environment tends to cost LP6 more than it gives.
 </p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

